## IAM Roles for EC2 (Instance Profiles)

This is how you give an EC2 instance permission to call AWS APIs — without putting credentials on the instance.

```bash
# 1. Create a policy
aws iam create-policy \
  --policy-name app-s3-read \
  --policy-document file://s3-read-policy.json

# s3-read-policy.json:
# {
#   "Version": "2012-10-17",
#   "Statement": [{
#     "Effect": "Allow",
#     "Action": ["s3:GetObject", "s3:ListBucket"],
#     "Resource": [
#       "arn:aws:s3:::my-app-bucket",
#       "arn:aws:s3:::my-app-bucket/*"
#     ]
#   }]
# }

# 2. Create a role with EC2 trust policy
aws iam create-role \
  --role-name ec2-app-role \
  --assume-role-policy-document '{
    "Version": "2012-10-17",
    "Statement": [{
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Principal": {"Service": "ec2.amazonaws.com"},
      "Action": "sts:AssumeRole"
    }]
  }'

# 3. Attach the policy to the role
aws iam attach-role-policy \
  --role-name ec2-app-role \
  --policy-arn arn:aws:iam::ACCOUNT_ID:policy/app-s3-read

# 4. Create an instance profile and add the role
aws iam create-instance-profile --instance-profile-name ec2-app-profile
aws iam add-role-to-instance-profile \
  --instance-profile-name ec2-app-profile \
  --role-name ec2-app-role

# 5. Launch EC2 with this profile
aws ec2 run-instances \
  --iam-instance-profile Name=ec2-app-profile \
  ...

# 6. Verify from inside the instance
aws s3 ls s3://my-app-bucket   # should work without any credentials configured
aws sts get-caller-identity    # shows the assumed role
```

